\chapter{The let statement in ECMA 6}

The let statement declares a block scope local variable, optionally initializing it to a value. To currently use in in Chrome you need to inclue a `use strict` directive.

\begin{codeblock}

// Example of let scoping rules
'use strict';

var a = 5;
var b = 10;

if (a === 5) {
  let a = 4; // The scope is inside the if-block
  var b = 1; // The scope is inside the function

  log(a);  // 4
  log(b);  // 1
} 

log(a); // 5
log(b); // 1
\end{codeblock}


See also David Leonard's [cheatsheet](https://github.com/DrkSephy/es6-cheatsheet)